Before examining the data, I would expect those who report more exercise to have a lower BMI, while those who report less exercise to have a higher BMI, on average. This would be a negative correlation between BMI and reported exercise.

??corruptDF

In the corruptDF (renamed cdf) dataset, the collumn CPI2017 captures the degree of corruption in the given country in 2017 ranging from corrupt (0) to clean (100), formally known as the Corruption Perceptions Index.

HDI2017 measures the overall development of a particular country in 2017 taking into account demographic factors such as education and income, as well as the nationâs longevity. HDI stands for the Human Development Index and ranges from developing (0) to more developed (1).

Question 3

ggplot(cdf,
       aes(x = CPI2017, 
           y = HDI2017)) +
  geom_point()

The above scatterplot displaying the relationship between CPI2017 and HDI2017 shows a weak positive linear relationship. The spread of the data decreases as the CPI2017 decreases as it approaches 100, as the residuals are greater among the lower CPI2017 countries.

Question 4

ggplot(cdf,
       aes(x = CPI2017, 
           y = HDI2017)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Relationship between HDI2017 and CPI2017") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

I added the geom_smooth() function to the scatterplot code to include the blue line on the graph that helps illustrate the relationship between CPI2017 and HDI2017. The above scatterplot displays the lm or âlinear modelâ method, while the below scatterplot displays the gam or âgeneralized additive modelâ method. The differences are that the lm method has a straight blue âbest fitâ line, whlie the gam method has a curved/bent line that is slightly concave down. I prefer the linear model (lm) method because the straight line is more aesthetic and easier to observe how each data point aligns with overall pattern, like when observing residuals.

ggplot(cdf,
       aes(x = CPI2017, 
           y = HDI2017)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Relationship between HDI2017 and CPI2017") +
  geom_smooth(method = "gam", se = FALSE)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Question 5

ggplot(cdf,
       aes(x = CPI2017, 
           y = HDI2017, 
           fill = region)) +
  geom_point(color = "navy", fill = "grey") +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', 
              color = "black")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

After adding color to the graph so that each point is grouped by region, I can see the different linear relationships between CPI2017 and HDI2017 for each region to compare them. However, it is very cluttered and difficult to see the patterns. A solution that allows you to see the trends by region in a way that is more legible is to use the facet_wrap(~region) function that makes a separate graph for each value of the designated variable (region) as shown below.

ggplot(cdf,
       aes(x = CPI2017, 
           y = HDI2017)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = region)) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', 
              color = "black") +
facet_wrap(~region)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

After comparing the 6 different graph displaying the relationship between CPI2017 and HDI2017 within each region, I can see that the Americas, Asia Pacific, MENA, and SSA regions have a steeper positive relationship, while the EU W. Europe and East EU Cemt Asia regions have a more flat line. East EU Cemt Asia and EU W. Europe have the least spread, while SSA seems to have the greatest residuals on average. EU W. Europe also has the highest HDI2017 for each point on average, as no countries have an HDI2017 lower than 0.8.

I experimented with the scale_x_reverse() function to reverse the scale of my x-axis, which is CPI2017. Now instead of going from 0-100, it goes from 100-0, from left to right.
